Installation of VS Code:
1.	Download VS Code:
•	Visit the official Visual Studio Code website.
•	Click the "Download for Windows" button.
•	Save the downloaded .exe file to your computer.
2.	Install VS Code:
•	Double-click the downloaded .exe file to start the installation process.
•	Follow the on-screen instructions: accept the agreement, choose the installation location (default is fine), select additional tasks (like creating a desktop icon), and click "Next."
•	Click "Install" to begin the installation.
•	Once the installation is complete, click "Finish" to launch Visual Studio Code.
3.	Prerequisites:
•	Ensure you have administrative privileges to install software on your computer.
•	Install the latest version of Git if you plan to use Git for version control.
First-time Setup:
1.	Initial Configurations:
•	Theme: Go to File > Preferences > Color Theme to select a theme that suits your preference.
•	Font Size: Go to File > Preferences > Settings, search for "Font Size" and adjust it to your liking.
2.	Extensions:
•	Open the Extensions view by clicking the Extensions icon in the Activity Bar on the side of the window or pressing Ctrl+Shift+X.
•	Search for and install essential extensions like: ESLint: For linting JavaScript and TypeScript, Prettier: For code formatting, Live Server: For a quick development live server with live browser reload, Python: If you plan to work with Python.
User Interface Overview:
1.	Activity Bar: Located on the far left, it provides access to different views such as Explorer, Search, Source Control, Debug, and Extensions.
2.	Side Bar: Displays different views and functions depending on the activity selected in the Activity Bar. For example, the Explorer view shows your project files and folders.
3.	Editor Group: The main area where you edit your files. You can split the editor into multiple groups to view and edit multiple files side-by-side.
4.	Status Bar: Located at the bottom, it displays information about the opened project and the current file, such as line and column number, encoding, and Git branch.
Command Palette:
1.	What is the Command Palette: The Command Palette provides quick access to all VS Code commands?
2.	Accessing the Command Palette: Press Ctrl+Shift+P (Windows/Linux) or Cmd+Shift+P (Mac) to open it.
3.	Examples of Common Tasks:
•	Opening files: Type Open File and select a file.
•	Running a build task: Type Run Task and select the task.
•	Installing extensions: Type Extensions: Install Extensions.
Extensions in VS Code:
1.	Role of Extensions: Extensions enhance the functionality of VS Code by adding new features and tools.
2.	Finding and Installing Extensions:
•	Click the Extensions icon in the Activity Bar.
•	Use the search bar to find extensions.
•	Click Install on the desired extension.
3.	Managing Extensions: Installed extensions can be managed from the Extensions view. Click the gear icon next to an extension to disable, uninstall, or configure it.
4.	Essential Extensions for Web Development:
•	ESLint
•	Prettier
•	Live Server
•	Debugger for Chrome
Integrated Terminal:
1.	Opening the Integrated Terminal: Go to View > Terminal or press Ctrl+ (Windows/Linux) or Cmd+ (Mac).
2.	Using the Integrated Terminal: You can run command-line tools directly within VS Code, making it convenient to execute Git commands, run scripts, or compile code.
3.	Advantages:
•	Eliminates the need to switch between VS Code and an external terminal.
•	Supports multiple terminal sessions.
File and Folder Management:
1.	Creating Files and Folders: Right-click in the Explorer view and select New File or New Folder.
2.	Opening Files and Folders:
•	Click File > Open File or Open Folder.
•	Use Ctrl+P to quickly open files by typing their name.
3.	Navigating Files and Directories:
•	Use the Explorer view to browse your files.
•	Use Ctrl+Tab to switch between open files.
Settings and Preferences:
1.	Finding and Customizing Settings:
•	Go to File > Preferences > Settings or press Ctrl+,
•	Use the search bar to find specific settings.
2.	Examples:
•	Changing the Theme: Search for "Color Theme" and select a new theme.
•	Adjusting Font Size: Search for "Font Size" and change the value.
•	Keybindings: Go to File > Preferences > Keyboard Shortcuts to customize keybindings.
Debugging in VS Code:
1.	Setting Up Debugging:
•	Open a file to debug and set breakpoints by clicking in the gutter next to the line numbers.
•	Go to the Run view by clicking the Run icon in the Activity Bar.
•	Click Create a launch.json file and select the appropriate environment.
2.	Starting Debugging: Press F5 to start debugging.
3.	Key Debugging Features:
•	Breakpoints: Pause the execution at specific lines.
•	Watch Variables: Monitor the values of variables.
•	Call Stack: View the stack trace of function calls.
•	Debug Console: Execute commands and evaluate expressions.
Using Source Control:
1.	Integrating Git with VS Code:
•	Ensure Git is installed on your system.
•	Open the Source Control view by clicking the Source Control icon in the Activity Bar.
2.	Initializing a Repository: Click Initialize Repository in the Source Control view.
3.	Making Commits:
•	Stage changes by clicking the + icon next to the files.
•	Enter a commit message and click Commit.
4.	Pushing Changes to GitHub:
•	Click the ... menu in the Source Control view and select Push.
•	Follow the prompts to authenticate with GitHub and push your changes.
